Intuition
so after looking at probelm i realized this is a sliding window problem and in this problem the size of window is not fixed , so my thinking was i will find frequency map of characters and if length of frequency map is less than length of substring so duplicates exist , so i will remove characters from frequency map till length of frequency map is equal to length of substring , then i will return the maximum possible length of substring with unique characters

Approach
initalize low = 0, high = 0 , low for removing characters and high for adding characters into frequency map ,
create empty dictionary for counting frequency of characters , freq = {}
result = 0 (if there exists no charcaters in string or string is empty)

traverse the substring loop condition
for high in range (len(s)):
add characters into freq map ,
calculate length of substring

check for wrong condition : while len(freq) < length of substring
remove characters from substring
move low by +1
again calaculate length of updated substring

when condition is correct : len(freq) == length of substring
calaculate length
update result = max(result , length)

return result

Complexity
Time complexity:
O(n)
Space complexity:
O(1) for lower case alphabets , O(n) for general case because we created a dictionary
Code
class Solution:
    def lengthOfLongestSubstring(self, s: str) -> int:
        low = 0 
        high = 0
        result = 0
        freq = {}

        for high in range(len(s)):
            freq[s[high]] = freq.get(s[high],0) + 1
            length_window = high - low + 1
            while len(freq) < length_window:
                freq[s[low]] -= 1
                if freq[s[low]] == 0:
                    del freq[s[low]]
                low += 1
                length_window = high - low + 1
            length = high - low + 1
            result = max(result , length)
        return result
